							</td>
							<td></td>
							<td class="fragment" data-fragment-index="100">
								Spline Link
							</td>
						</tr></table>
						<div class="fragment" data-fragment-index="100">
							<p style="margin-top: 25px; clear: both">Spline link</p>
							<div class="post">
									<img src="images/spline-shaft_section.png" height="200px"  />
									<img src="images/spline-shaft_anim.gif"  />
									<img src="images/spline-shaft_iso.png" height="200px"  />
							</div>
						</div>
						<aside class="notes">
							<div style="font-size: .75em"data-markdown>
								* Up till now functionality has not been mentioned! Our ultimate objective is to bind form to function,
								a link that is well-established in the literature.
								* If this connection is to be made as this stage, we know that we can interpret a Cyl Interference,
								a CI, as a Threaded Link, an FI.
								* However, it is only part of the truth, as a Cyl Interference can also represent a Spline link.
								An FI that is show in the image and that transmits rotation while allowing translation.
								* In order to resolve this ambiguous interpretation, more information must be incorporated,
								especially those about the context of the interface. 
							</div>
						</aside>
					</section>

					<section>
						<h2>Functional interpretations</h2>
						<ul>
							<li>Hierarchical representation of interfaces (<em>taxonomies</em>).</li>
							<li>Each CI is associated multiple FIs acc. a <em>dictionary</em>.</li>
						</ul>
						<img src="images/taxo_ci_fi.png"  width="75%" />
						<div class="override">
							<div class="conclusion fragment zoom-out">
								Geometric and functional <em>knowledge structuring</em> at the interface level.
							</div>
						</div>
						<aside class="notes">
							<ul>
								<li>At this stage, however, we are interested in assigning <b>all</b> possible functional interpretations to 
								a given geometric config. represented by a CI.</li>
								<li>To this end, we organize geometric and functional knowledge at the interface level in hierarchies
								called FI and CI taxonomies resp.</li>
								<li>Functional interpretation then happens at the leaf-level of those taxo.
								Each CI is associated potentially to multiple FIs according to a <em>dictionary</em> that reflects mainstream industrial conventions.</li>
								<li>This frames funct. knowledge into a preliminary structure.</li>
							</ul>
						</aside>
					</section>
					
					<section data-transition-speed="slow">
						<h2>Relevant structure</h2>
						<table class="ladder" id="meter1">
